{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2420527b-09d5-4fa6-9a5f-a8050b973f92","content":"Neither — use **`dotnet watch`**.\n\n`dotnet watch` is the command that enables hot reload. It monitors your source files and automatically re-runs/re-builds when changes are detected:\n\n```bash\n# For a test project like yours:\ndotnet watch test\n\n# For an app project:\ndotnet watch run\n```\n\n- **`dotnet test`** / **`dotnet run`** execute once and exit — no file watching or hot reload.\n- **`dotnet watch`** wraps them, adding the hot-reload behavior.\n\nSince your project (`TestProject.csproj`) is a test project, you'd use:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6ef4a479-890d-4d46-ab1f-979c0bbec9ae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET hot reload - specifically whether `dotnet test` or `dotnet run` benefits from hot reload. Let me look at the project files to understand their setup.","outputTokens":210},"id":"a2ad0628-b0e0-4638-93bd-eba72ef379de","timestamp":"2026-04-07T13:04:38.830Z","parentId":"34f09c3d-81f8-4574-8917-49c1c21baebe"}
